cess-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|Messaging applications targeted for the workplace <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slack.com/|title=Where work happens|last=Slack|website=Slack|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Snapchat]]\n|[[Snap Inc.]]\n|210 million daily active users (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oberlo.com/blog/snapchat-statistics|title=10 Snapchat Statistics Everyone Should Know in 2020 [Infographic]|date=2020-01-03|website=Oberlo|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|Time-limited messaging and pictures <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snapchat.com/|title=Snapchat - The fastest way to share a moment!|website=www.snapchat.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Telegram (software)|Telegram]]\n|[[Telegram FZ LLC]]\n|300 million monthly active users (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/complaints/2019/comp-pr2019-212.pdf|title=SEC vs Telegram|last=|first=|date=|website=SEC.Gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|End-to-end encrypted cloud-based instant messaging <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegram.org/|title=Telegram \u2013 a new era of messaging|website=Telegram|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Tencent QQ]]\n|[[Tencent Holdings Limited]]\n|807 million (2018) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/227352/number-of-active-tencent-im-user-accounts-in-china/|title=China: number of monthly active Tencent QQ IM user accounts 2018|website=Statista|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|Messaging application\u00a0 with online games, animations, and photos <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clickz.com/qq-the-biggest-digital-platform-youve-never-heard-of/113476/|title=QQ: The biggest digital platform you've never heard of|date=2017-10-09|website=ClickZ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Viber]]\n|[[Rakuten]]\n|1.095 billion registered users <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/316414/viber-messenger-registered-users/|title=Viber: number of registered users 2019|website=Statista|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|Japanese cross-platform messaging application <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/02/22/viber-chatbot-charge/|title=Rakuten\u2019s Viber chat app plans to charge to operate chatbots in controversial move|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[WeChat]]\n|[[Tencent Holdings Limited]]\n|1.132 billion monthly active users (Q2\u2019 2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/255778/number-of-active-wechat-messenger-accounts/|title=WeChat: number of users 2019|website=Statista|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|Multipurpose messaging, social, and payment application <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wechat.com/en/|title=WeChat - Free messaging and calling app|website=www.wechat.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[WhatsApp]]\n|[[Facebook]]\n|2 billion registered users (February 2020) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.whatsapp.com/two-billion-users-connecting-the-world-privately|title=WhatsApp|website=WhatsApp.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>; 500 million daily active users (March 2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/730306/whatsapp-status-dau/|title=WhatsApp Status daily active users 2019|website=Statista|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>;\n|Free texting and calling application for mobile phones and computers <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsapp.com/|title=WhatsApp|website=WhatsApp.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Features==\n\n=== Chat ===\nPrivate chat allows private conversation with another person or a group. The privacy aspect can also be enhanced as applications have a timer feature, like [[Snapchat]], where messages or conversations are automatically deleted once the time limit is reached. Public and group chat features allow users to communicate with multiple people at a time.\n\n=== Calls ===\nMany major messaging apps offer the call feature for user-to-user calls, conference calls, and voice messages. The call functionality is useful for professionals who utilize the application for work purposes and as a hands-free method. \n\n=== Games ===\nSome messaging applications include in-app games for entertainment. For example, the [[Facebook Messenger]] application has a built in option to play computer games with people in a chat, including games like [[Tetris]] and [[Blackjack]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itechfever.com/best-facebook-messenger-games/|title=17 Best Facebook Messenger Games To Play In 2020|date=2018-05-02|website=iTechFever|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Payments ===\nThough a relatively new feature, peer-to-peer payments are available on major messaging platforms. This functionality allows individuals to use one application for both communication and financial tasks. The lack of a service fee also makes messaging apps advantageous to financial applications like [[Venmo]] or [[PayPal]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobilemarketer.com/ex/mobilemarketer/cms/news/messaging/21840.html|title=Why messaging apps are striking gold with peer-to-peer payments {{!}} Mobile Marketer|website=www.mobilemarketer.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Major platforms such as Facebook messenger and [[WeChat]] already offer a payment feature, and this functionality is likely to become a standard amongst messaging apps competing in the market.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Encryption ==\n[[Encryption]] is the primary method that messaging apps use to protect user\u2019s data privacy and security. SMS messages are not encrypted, making them insecure, as the content of each SMS message is visible to mobile carriers and governments and can be intercepted by a third party.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2018/12/25/cybersecurity-101-guide-encrypted-messaging-apps/|title=Cybersecurity 101: How to choose and use an encrypted messaging app|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> SMS messages also leak [[metadata]], or information about the message that is not the message content itself, such as phone numbers of the sender and recipient, which can identify the people involved in the conversation.<ref name=\":5\" /> SMS messages can also be spoofed and the sender of the message can be edited to impersonate another person.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nMessaging applications on the market that use encryption include Signal, WhatsApp, Wire and iMessage (which uses [[end-to-end encryption]]).<ref name=\":5\" /> Applications that have been criticized for lacking or poor encryption methods include Telegram and Confide, as both are prone to error.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Future development ==\n\n=== Artificial Intelligence ===\n[[Artificial intelligence]] (AI) is commonly implemented in SMS messaging to handle large amounts of messages and data.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2019/11/mobile-messaging-artificial-intelligence-advancements/|title=Taking the Mess Out of Messaging|date=2019-11-26|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> AI technology first classifies the content of each message as personal, promotional, or transactional.<ref name=\":1\" /> It then filters through the message to display key information for each mobile user.<ref name=\":1\" /> As it trains itself by sorting millions of sample messages to take into account syntax and semantic patterns per each message, it learns to classify messages and extract key components of each message, such as dates, numbers, and other information.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Machine Learning ===\nIn 2016, Google introduced a new intelligent messaging app that incorporates machine learning technology called Allo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016-05-18-google-allo.html|title=Google's Allo puts AI in a messaging app|website=Engadget|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Instant messaging]]\n*[[Social media]]\n*[[Text messaging]]\n*[[SMS]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{ cite web | url = http://blogs.rediff.com/thinko/2019/09/12/meet-the-new-age-creators-from-bharat-helos-platform-empowering-local-content-creators-2/\n | publisher = Rediff.com| title = Meet the new-age creators from 'Bharat' - Helo's platform empowering local content creators }}\n\n{{Mobile phones}}\n{{Instant messaging}}\n\n[[Category:Social networking services]]\n[[Category:Instant messaging]]\n[[Category:Online chat]]\n[[Category:Text messaging]]\n", "name_user": "Acprisip", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Messaging_apps"}
{"title_page": "Gabe Newell", "text_new": "{{short description|American computer programmer and businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gabe Newell\n| image              = The International 2018 (43263984845) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Newell at The International in 2018\n| birth_name         = Gabe Logan Newell\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1962|11|3}}\n| birth_place        = [[Colorado]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Seattle]], Washington<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/gabe-newell/ |title=Gabe Newell |website=Forbes |language=en |access-date=2018-12-15}}</ref>\n| other_names        = Gaben\n| alma_mater         = [[Harvard University]] (dropped out)\n| known_for          = Co-founding [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]\n| net_worth          = {{US$|3.5&nbsp;billion|link=yes}} ({{As of|2018|12|alt=November 2019)}}<ref name=\"Forbes\"/>\n| title              = [[President (corporate title)|President]] of Valve\n| spouse             = {{Marriage|Lisa Mennet Newell|1996}}\n| children           = 2\n| awards             = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|[[BAFTA Fellowship]] (2013)|[[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences#Hall of Fame|AIAS]] Hall of Fame Award (2013)<ref>{{cite web|title=D.I.C.E Special Awards|url=http://www.interactive.org/special_awards/details.asp?idSpecialAwards=25|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>}}\n}}\n\n'''Gabe Logan Newell''' (born {{birth date|1962|11|3}}), commonly known by his nickname '''Gaben''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|g|e\u026a|b|\u02c8|\u025b|n}}), is an American [[computer programmer]] and businessman best known as the co-founder of the [[video game development]] and [[digital distribution]] company [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]. Born in [[Colorado]], he attended [[Harvard University]] in the early 1980s, but dropped out and worked for [[Microsoft]], where he worked as a producer for some of the early [[Windows]] [[operating system]]s.\n\nWhile still working at the company during the mid-1990s, Newell and his co-worker [[Mike Harrington]] became convinced that video games were the future of entertainment after playing [[id Software]]'s ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' and ''[[Quake (video game)|Quake]]''. Intrigued by the prospect of having their own game development studio, Newell and Harrington left Microsoft in 1996 to found Valve, where Newell remains [[President (corporate title)|president]].\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Gabe Newell - 2002 (cropped).jpg|left|thumb|Newell in 2002]]\nNewell was born in [[Colorado]] on November 3, 1962, later attending [[Davis Senior High School (California)|Davis Senior High School]] in [[Davis, California]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/this-is-gabe-newell-in-his-freshman-year-of-high-school-5928006 |title=This is Gabe Newell in his freshman year of high school |last=Good |first=Owen |date=July 21, 2012 |website=Kotaku |access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Following that, he attended [[Harvard University]] from 1980 until 1983, but dropped out before graduating to work for the American technology company [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2005/1212/064.html | title = It's A Mod, Mod Underworld | last = Barret | first = Victoria | date = December 12, 2005 | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate = February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"LinkedIn\">{{cite web|title=Gabe Newell|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/gabenewell|website=LinkedIn|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> Newell then spent the next thirteen years working at the company, serving as a producer of the [[Windows 1.01]], [[Windows 1.02|1.02]], and [[Windows 1.03|1.03]] [[operating system]]s.<ref name=\"Creative Minds\">{{cite web | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/172835/interviews/creative-minds-gabe-newell/ | title = Creative Minds: Gabe Newell | author = CVG Staff | date = September 28, 2007 | website = [[Computer and Video Games]] | publisher = [[Future plc]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141211153904/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/172835/interviews/creative-minds-gabe-newell/ | archivedate = December 11, 2014 | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Newell later stated that he learned more during his first three months at Microsoft than he ever did at Harvard, explaining one of the reasons why he had dropped out.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tosie|first1=Anthony|title=Gabe Newell: I learned more in three months at Microsoft than entire time at Harvard|url=https://www.neowin.net/news/gabe-newell-i-learned-more-in-three-months-at-microsoft-than-entire-time-at-harvard|website=neowin.net|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref> Inspired by [[Michael Abrash]], who left Microsoft to work on the computer game ''[[Quake (video game)|Quake]]'' at [[id Software]], Newell and another Microsoft employee, [[Mike Harrington]], left Microsoft to found [[Valve Corporation|Valve]] in 1996.<ref name=\"Creative Minds\" /> Newell and Harrington used their money to fund Valve through the development of ''[[Half-Life (video game)|Half-Life]]'' and the [[GoldSrc]] game engine.\n\nDuring production on ''[[Half-Life 2]]'', he spent several months focusing on the [[Steam (software)|Steam]] project.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-final-hours-of-half-life-2/1100-6112889/ | title = The Final Hours of Half-Life 2 | last = Keighley | first = Geoff | date = November 12, 2004 | website = [[GameSpot]] | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Newell openly expressed his displeasure over developing his software for gaming consoles, particularly the [[PlayStation 3]]. In regard to the system, Newell was once quoted as claiming that developing processes for the console in general was \"a waste of everybody's time\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/ps3-a-waste-of-time-says-valves-newell | title = PS3 a \"waste of time,\" says Valve's Newell | last = Androvich | first = Mark | date = October 11, 2007 | website = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] | publisher = [[Gamer Network]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> and \"a disaster on many levels ... I'd say, even at this late date, they should just cancel it and do a do-over. Just say, 'This was a horrible disaster and we're sorry and we're going to stop selling this and stop trying to convince people to develop for it'.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/155309/valve-ps3-a-total-disaster-on-so-many-levels/ | title = Gabe Newell: PS3 \"a waste of everybody's time\" | last = Bishop | first = Stuart | date = January 15, 2007 | website = [[Computer and Video Games]] | publisher = [[Future plc]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141223172938/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/155309/valve-ps3-a-total-disaster-on-so-many-levels/ | archivedate = December 23, 2014 | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Nevertheless, at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] in 2010, Newell appeared on stage at Sony's keynote; while acknowledging his past outspoken comments on console development, he discussed the open nature of Sony's PlayStation 3 platform, and announced ''[[Portal 2]]'' for the console, remarking that with [[Steamworks]] support it would be the best version for any console.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/portal-2-coming-to-playstation-3 | title = Portal 2 coming to PlayStation 3 |last = Bramwell | first = Tom | date = June 15, 2010 | website = [[Eurogamer]] | publisher = [[Gamer Network]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Newell has also criticized the [[Xbox Live]] service, referring to it as \"a train wreck\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/5634305/valve-figured-microsoft-would-fix-the-xbox-live-train-wreck | title = Valve Figured Microsoft Would Fix The Xbox Live \"Train Wreck\" | last = Fahey | first = Mike | date = September 9, 2010 | website = [[Kotaku]] | publisher = [[Gawker Media]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> He was also critical of Microsoft's [[Windows 8]] operating system, calling it a \"catastrophe\" and \"a threat\" to the open nature of [[PC gaming]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-18996377 | title = Valve boss Gabe Newell calls Windows 8 a 'catastrophe' | website = [[BBC News]] | publisher = [[BBC]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, ''[[Forbes]]'' named Newell as \"A Name You Should Know\", primarily for his work on Steam having partnerships with multiple major developers.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/oliverchiang/2010/11/13/names-you-need-to-know-in-2011-gabe-newell/ | title = Names You Need to Know in 2011: Gabe Newell | last = Chiang | first = Oliver | date = November 13, 2010 | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate = February 2, 2016}}</ref> In March 2013, Newell received the [[BAFTA Fellowship]] award for his contributions to the [[video game industry]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bafta.org/press/press-releases/valves-gabe-newell-to-be-honoured-with-bafta-fellowship | title = Valve's Gabe Newell to be Honoured with BAFTA Fellowship | date = February 25, 2013 | website = [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> In October 2017, ''Forbes'' listed him among the 100 richest people in the United States, with an estimated net worth of {{USD}}5.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/gabe-newell-is-worth-55-billion-according-to-forbes/ | title = Gabe Newell is worth $5.5 billion, according to Forbes | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = October 19, 2017 | accessdate = October 19, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref><ref name=\"net worth\">{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/profile/gabe-newell/?list=billionaires | title = Forbes Lists - Gabe Newell | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate = October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Gabe Newell GDC 2010.jpg|thumb|Newell at the 2010 [[Game Developers Conference]]]]\nNewell formerly suffered from [[Fuchs' dystrophy]], a congenital disease which affects the [[cornea]], but was cured by two cornea transplants in 2006 and 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2011/0228/technology-gabe-newell-videogames-valve-online-mayhem.html | title = The Master of Online Mayhem | last = Chiang | first = Oliver | date = February 9, 2011 | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> He married Lisa Mennet (now Lisa Mennet Newell) on the same day he founded Valve with Harrington.<ref>{{cite AV media |title=Icons: Half-Life |author=[[G4tv]] |date=16 November 2004 |time=2:20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://spong.com/article/8051/Valve-wins-round-one-in-Half-Life-distribution-debacle | title = Valve wins round one in Half-Life distribution debacle | author = Staff | date = November 30, 2004 | website = SPOnG | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=valve_neh>{{cite web|title=Valve Handbook for New Employees|url=https://steamcdn-a.akamaihd.net/apps/valve/Valve_NewEmployeeHandbook.pdf|publisher=Valve|accessdate=September 1, 2013|page=19}}</ref> The couple has two sons, including Gray.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/pacificnw/2003/0518/cover02.html |title=TUNED TO THE DUNES |date=2003 |website=[[The Seattle Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/profile/gabe-newell/ | title = Gabe Newell | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> The birth of Gray in the late 1990s served as inspiration for the [[Boss (video gaming)#Final boss|final boss]] of ''Half-Life'', as the couple considered childbirth to be the most frightening thing they could think of at the time.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Alex |title=Half-Life's Final Boss Was Based On Gabe Newell's Son (Being Born) |url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2018/02/half-lifes-final-boss-was-based-on-gabe-newells-son-being-born/ |website=Kotaku |accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Newell stated that some of his favorite video games were ''[[Super Mario 64]]'', ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'', and a [[Burroughs Corporation|Burroughs]] mainframe version of ''[[Star Trek]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/296735/features/gabe-newell-my-3-favourite-games/ | title = Gabe Newell: My 3 favourite games | last = Ingham | first = Tim | date = April 4, 2011 | website = [[Computer and Video Games]] | publisher = [[Future plc]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150211164700/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/296735/features/gabe-newell-my-3-favourite-games/ | archivedate = February 11, 2015 | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> ''Doom'' convinced him that games were the future of entertainment, and ''Super Mario 64'' convinced him that [[Video games as an art form|games are a form of art]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Newell is also a [[Brony|fan]] of the animated series ''[[My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/5899357/gabe-newell-just-made-my-little-pony-fans-extremely-happy | title = Gabe Newell Just Made My Little Pony Fans Extremely Happy | last = Fahey | first = Mike | date = April 12, 2012 | website = [[Kotaku]] | publisher = [[Gawker Media]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> In 2013, Newell was added to the [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]] Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-11-15-gabe-newell-named-as-next-aias-hall-of-famer | title = Gabe Newell named as next AIAS Hall of Famer | last = Purchese | first = Robert | date = November 15, 2012 | website = [[Eurogamer]] | publisher = [[Gamer Network]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Newell also recorded a voice pack for ''[[Dota 2]]'', a Valve-developed game, which referenced many previous statements and phrases from himself in a humorous manner.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horti |first1=Samuel |title=Gabe Newell comes to Dota 2 in wonderfully deadpan voice pack |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/gabe-newell-comes-to-dota-2-with-wonderfully-deadpan-voice-pack/ |website=PC Gamer |accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWithin the gaming community, he is jokingly known as \"Gaben\", which is derived from his work email address.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/108247-Gabe-Newell-Gives-Away-Personal-Steam-Password | title = Gabe Newell Gives Away Personal Steam Password | last = Goldman | first = Tom | date = March 5, 2011 | website = [[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] | publisher = [[Defy Media]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Newell stated that he has tried to grow into his public image: \"They hug me when they run into me. I'm not a hugging person, but that's what they want. I was with my kids the first time that happened in public, and my kids were pretty cool with it. But I wasn't. 'Dad, roll with it.' Even now, I'm learning from our customers.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/01/06/gabe-newell-on-valves-intimate-relationship-with-its-customers/ | title = Gabe Newell on Valve's intimate relationship with its customers | last = Peterson | first = Andrea | date = January 6, 2014 | website = [[The Washington Post]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2007/11/21/rps-exclusive-gabe-newell-interview/ | title = RPS Exclusive: Gabe Newell Interview | last = Walker | first = John | date = November 21, 2007 | website = [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/valves-gabe-newell-interview | title = Valve's Gabe Newell | last = Bramwell | first = Tom | date = August 29, 2007 | website = [[Eurogamer]] | publisher = [[Gamer Network]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-final-hours-of-half-life-2/1100-6112889/ | title = The Final Hours of Half-Life 2 | last = Keighley | first = Geoff | date = November 12, 2004 | website = [[GameSpot]] | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://hl2central.net/?id=1480 | title = An interview with Gabe Newell | author = Psycho_byte | date = June 26, 2003 | website = HL2Central | publisher = Game Central Network | access-date = February 9, 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180811230617/http://hl2central.net/?id=1480 | archive-date = August 11, 2018 | url-status = dead }}\n* {{cite web | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/01/03/gabe-newell-on-what-makes-valve-tick/ | title = Gabe Newell on what makes Valve tick | last = Peterson | first = Andrea | date = January 3, 2014 | website = [[The Washington Post]]}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Gabe Newell}}\n* {{Wikiquote-inline|Gabe Newell}}\n* {{Spoken Wikipedia|En-Gabe Newell.ogg|2019-12-02}}\n\n{{BAFTA Academy Fellowship Award}}\n{{Valve}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newell, Gabe}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:American technology company founders]]\n[[Category:American video game designers]]\n[[Category:BAFTA fellows]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Microsoft employees]]\n[[Category:Valve Corporation people]]\n[[Category:Video game producers]]\n[[Category:People from Davis, California]]\n[[Category:Davis Senior High School (California) alumni]]\n[[Category:Game Developers Conference Pioneer Award recipients]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American computer programmer and businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gabe Newell\n| image              = The International 2018 (43263984845) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Newell at The International in 2018\n| birth_name         = Gabe Logan Newell\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1962|11|3}}\n| birth_place        = [[Colorado]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Seattle]], Washington<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/gabe-newell/ |title=Gabe Newell |website=Forbes |language=en |access-date=2018-12-15}}</ref>\n| other_names        = Gaben\n| alma_mater         = [[Harvard University]] (dropped out)\n| known_for          = Co-founding [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]\n| net_worth          = {{US$|3.5&nbsp;billion|link=yes}} ({{As of|2018|12|alt=November 2019)}}<ref name=\"Forbes\"/>\n| title              = [[President (corporate title)|President]] of Valve\n| spouse             = {{Marriage|Lisa Mennet Newell|1996}}\n| children           = 2\n| awards             = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|[[BAFTA Fellowship]] (2013)|[[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences#Hall of Fame|AIAS]] Hall of Fame Award (2013)<ref>{{cite web|title=D.I.C.E Special Awards|url=http://www.interactive.org/special_awards/details.asp?idSpecialAwards=25|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>}}\n}}\n\n'''Gabe Logan Newell''' (born {{birth date|1962|11|3}}), commonly known by his nickname '''Gaben''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|g|e\u026a|b|\u02c8|\u025b|n}}), is an American [[computer programmer]] and businessman best known as the co-founder of the [[video game development]] and [[digital distribution]] company [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]. Born in [[Colorado]], he attended [[Harvard University]] in the early 1980s, but dropped out and worked for [[Microsoft]], where he worked as a producer for some of the early [[Windows]] [[operating system]]s.\n\nWhile still working at the company during the mid-1990s, Newell and his co-worker [[Mike Harrington]] became convinced that video games were the future of entertainment after playing [[id Software]]'s ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' and ''[[Quake (video game)|Quake]]''. Intrigued by the prospect of having their own game development studio, Newell and Harrington left Microsoft in 1996 to found Valve, where Newell remains [[President (corporate title)|president]].\n\n== Career ==\nNewell was born in [[Colorado]] on November 3, 1962, later attending [[Davis Senior High School (California)|Davis Senior High School]] in [[Davis, California]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/this-is-gabe-newell-in-his-freshman-year-of-high-school-5928006 |title=This is Gabe Newell in his freshman year of high school |last=Good |first=Owen |date=July 21, 2012 |website=Kotaku |access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Following that, he attended [[Harvard University]] from 1980 until 1983, but dropped out before graduating to work for the American technology company [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2005/1212/064.html | title = It's A Mod, Mod Underworld | last = Barret | first = Victoria | date = December 12, 2005 | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate = February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"LinkedIn\">{{cite web|title=Gabe Newell|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/gabenewell|website=LinkedIn|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> Newell then spent the next thirteen years working at the company, serving as a producer of the [[Windows 1.01]], [[Windows 1.02|1.02]], and [[Windows 1.03|1.03]] [[operating system]]s.<ref name=\"Creative Minds\">{{cite web | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/172835/interviews/creative-minds-gabe-newell/ | title = Creative Minds: Gabe Newell | author = CVG Staff | date = September 28, 2007 | website = [[Computer and Video Games]] | publisher = [[Future plc]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141211153904/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/172835/interviews/creative-minds-gabe-newell/ | archivedate = December 11, 2014 | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Newell later stated that he learned more during his first three months at Microsoft than he ever did at Harvard, explaining one of the reasons why he had dropped out.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tosie|first1=Anthony|title=Gabe Newell: I learned more in three months at Microsoft than entire time at Harvard|url=https://www.neowin.net/news/gabe-newell-i-learned-more-in-three-months-at-microsoft-than-entire-time-at-harvard|website=neowin.net|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref> Inspired by [[Michael Abrash]], who left Microsoft to work on the computer game ''[[Quake (video game)|Quake]]'' at [[id Software]], Newell and another Microsoft employee, [[Mike Harrington]], left Microsoft to found [[Valve Corporation|Valve]] in 1996.<ref name=\"Creative Minds\" /> Newell and Harrington used their money to fund Valve through the development of ''[[Half-Life (video game)|Half-Life]]'' and the [[GoldSrc]] game engine.\n\nDuring production on ''[[Half-Life 2]]'', he spent several months focusing on the [[Steam (software)|Steam]] project.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-final-hours-of-half-life-2/1100-6112889/ | title = The Final Hours of Half-Life 2 | last = Keighley | first = Geoff | date = November 12, 2004 | website = [[GameSpot]] | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Newell openly expressed his displeasure over developing his software for gaming consoles, particularly the [[PlayStation 3]]. In regard to the system, Newell was once quoted as claiming that developing processes for the console in general was \"a waste of everybody's time\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/ps3-a-waste-of-time-says-valves-newell | title = PS3 a \"waste of time,\" says Valve's Newell | last = Androvich | first = Mark | date = October 11, 2007 | website = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] | publisher = [[Gamer Network]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> and \"a disaster on many levels ... I'd say, even at this late date, they should just cancel it and do a do-over. Just say, 'This was a horrible disaster and we're sorry and we're going to stop selling this and stop trying to convince people to develop for it'.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/155309/valve-ps3-a-total-disaster-on-so-many-levels/ | title = Gabe Newell: PS3 \"a waste of everybody's time\" | last = Bishop | first = Stuart | date = January 15, 2007 | website = [[Computer and Video Games]] | publisher = [[Future plc]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141223172938/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/155309/valve-ps3-a-total-disaster-on-so-many-levels/ | archivedate = December 23, 2014 | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Nevertheless, at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] in 2010, Newell appeared on stage at Sony's keynote; while acknowledging his past outspoken comments on console development, he discussed the open nature of Sony's PlayStation 3 platform, and announced ''[[Portal 2]]'' for the console, remarking that with [[Steamworks]] support it would be the best version for any console.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/portal-2-coming-to-playstation-3 | title = Portal 2 coming to PlayStation 3 |last = Bramwell | first = Tom | date = June 15, 2010 | website = [[Eurogamer]] | publisher = [[Gamer Network]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Newell has also criticized the [[Xbox Live]] service, referring to it as \"a train wreck\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/5634305/valve-figured-microsoft-would-fix-the-xbox-live-train-wreck | title = Valve Figured Microsoft Would Fix The Xbox Live \"Train Wreck\" | last = Fahey | first = Mike | date = September 9, 2010 | website = [[Kotaku]] | publisher = [[Gawker Media]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> He was also critical of Microsoft's [[Windows 8]] operating system, calling it a \"catastrophe\" and \"a threat\" to the open nature of [[PC gaming]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-18996377 | title = Valve boss Gabe Newell calls Windows 8 a 'catastrophe' | website = [[BBC News]] | publisher = [[BBC]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, ''[[Forbes]]'' named Newell as \"A Name You Should Know\", primarily for his work on Steam having partnerships with multiple major developers.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/oliverchiang/2010/11/13/names-you-need-to-know-in-2011-gabe-newell/ | title = Names You Need to Know in 2011: Gabe Newell | last = Chiang | first = Oliver | date = November 13, 2010 | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate = February 2, 2016}}</ref> In March 2013, Newell received the [[BAFTA Fellowship]] award for his contributions to the [[video game industry]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bafta.org/press/press-releases/valves-gabe-newell-to-be-honoured-with-bafta-fellowship | title = Valve's Gabe Newell to be Honoured with BAFTA Fellowship | date = February 25, 2013 | website = [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> In October 2017, ''Forbes'' listed him among the 100 richest people in the United States, with an estimated net worth of {{USD}}5.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/gabe-newell-is-worth-55-billion-according-to-forbes/ | title = Gabe Newell is worth $5.5 billion, according to Forbes | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = October 19, 2017 | accessdate = October 19, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref><ref name=\"net worth\">{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/profile/gabe-newell/?list=billionaires | title = Forbes Lists - Gabe Newell | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate = October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Gabe Newell GDC 2010.jpg|thumb|Newell at the 2010 [[Game Developers Conference]]]]\nNewell formerly suffered from [[Fuchs' dystrophy]], a congenital disease which affects the [[cornea]], but was cured by two cornea transplants in 2006 and 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2011/0228/technology-gabe-newell-videogames-valve-online-mayhem.html | title = The Master of Online Mayhem | last = Chiang | first = Oliver | date = February 9, 2011 | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> He married Lisa Mennet (now Lisa Mennet Newell) on the same day he founded Valve with Harrington.<ref>{{cite AV media |title=Icons: Half-Life |author=[[G4tv]] |date=16 November 2004 |time=2:20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://spong.com/article/8051/Valve-wins-round-one-in-Half-Life-distribution-debacle | title = Valve wins round one in Half-Life distribution debacle | author = Staff | date = November 30, 2004 | website = SPOnG | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=valve_neh>{{cite web|title=Valve Handbook for New Employees|url=https://steamcdn-a.akamaihd.net/apps/valve/Valve_NewEmployeeHandbook.pdf|publisher=Valve|accessdate=September 1, 2013|page=19}}</ref> The couple has two sons, including Gray.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/pacificnw/2003/0518/cover02.html |title=TUNED TO THE DUNES |date=2003 |website=[[The Seattle Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.forbes.com/profile/gabe-newell/ | title = Gabe Newell | website = [[Forbes]] | accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> The birth of Gray in the late 1990s served as inspiration for the [[Boss (video gaming)#Final boss|final boss]] of ''Half-Life'', as the couple considered childbirth to be the most frightening thing they could think of at the time.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Alex |title=Half-Life's Final Boss Was Based On Gabe Newell's Son (Being Born) |url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2018/02/half-lifes-final-boss-was-based-on-gabe-newells-son-being-born/ |website=Kotaku |accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Newell stated that some of his favorite video games were ''[[Super Mario 64]]'', ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'', and a [[Burroughs Corporation|Burroughs]] mainframe version of ''[[Star Trek]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/296735/features/gabe-newell-my-3-favourite-games/ | title = Gabe Newell: My 3 favourite games | last = Ingham | first = Tim | date = April 4, 2011 | website = [[Computer and Video Games]] | publisher = [[Future plc]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150211164700/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/296735/features/gabe-newell-my-3-favourite-games/ | archivedate = February 11, 2015 | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> ''Doom'' convinced him that games were the future of entertainment, and ''Super Mario 64'' convinced him that [[Video games as an art form|games are a form of art]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Newell is also a [[Brony|fan]] of the animated series ''[[My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/5899357/gabe-newell-just-made-my-little-pony-fans-extremely-happy | title = Gabe Newell Just Made My Little Pony Fans Extremely Happy | last = Fahey | first = Mike | date = April 12, 2012 | website = [[Kotaku]] | publisher = [[Gawker Media]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> In 2013, Newell was added to the [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]] Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-11-15-gabe-newell-named-as-next-aias-hall-of-famer | title = Gabe Newell named as next AIAS Hall of Famer | last = Purchese | first = Robert | date = November 15, 2012 | website = [[Eurogamer]] | publisher = [[Gamer Network]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Newell also recorded a voice pack for ''[[Dota 2]]'', a Valve-developed game, which referenced many previous statements and phrases from himself in a humorous manner.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horti |first1=Samuel |title=Gabe Newell comes to Dota 2 in wonderfully deadpan voice pack |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/gabe-newell-comes-to-dota-2-with-wonderfully-deadpan-voice-pack/ |website=PC Gamer |accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWithin the gaming community, he is jokingly known as \"Gaben\", which is derived from his work email address.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/108247-Gabe-Newell-Gives-Away-Personal-Steam-Password | title = Gabe Newell Gives Away Personal Steam Password | last = Goldman | first = Tom | date = March 5, 2011 | website = [[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] | publisher = [[Defy Media]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref> Newell stated that he has tried to grow into his public image: \"They hug me when they run into me. I'm not a hugging person, but that's what they want. I was with my kids the first time that happened in public, and my kids were pretty cool with it. But I wasn't. 'Dad, roll with it.' Even now, I'm learning from our customers.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/01/06/gabe-newell-on-valves-intimate-relationship-with-its-customers/ | title = Gabe Newell on Valve's intimate relationship with its customers | last = Peterson | first = Andrea | date = January 6, 2014 | website = [[The Washington Post]] | accessdate = February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2007/11/21/rps-exclusive-gabe-newell-interview/ | title = RPS Exclusive: Gabe Newell Interview | last = Walker | first = John | date = November 21, 2007 | website = [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/valves-gabe-newell-interview | title = Valve's Gabe Newell | last = Bramwell | first = Tom | date = August 29, 2007 | website = [[Eurogamer]] | publisher = [[Gamer Network]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-final-hours-of-half-life-2/1100-6112889/ | title = The Final Hours of Half-Life 2 | last = Keighley | first = Geoff | date = November 12, 2004 | website = [[GameSpot]] | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://hl2central.net/?id=1480 | title = An interview with Gabe Newell | author = Psycho_byte | date = Ju