{"title_page": "Henrico City (Virginia Company)", "text_new": "[[File:1634 Virginia Counties- Henrico Focus.jpg||thumb|upright=2.0|The eight shires of Virginia created in 1634 with Henrico in purple]]\n{{see also|Henricus}}\n\n{{Unreferenced|date=January 2008}}\n'''Henrico City''' (or '''Henrico Cittie''' as it was then called) was one of four incorporations established in the [[Virginia Colony]] in 1619 North America by the proprietor, the [[Virginia Company]] in it instructions to Governor Yeardley in 1618. <ref name=Kingsbury1933v3/>. These instructions incorporated most of the plantations and developments of Virginia into four boroughs or cities. These cities were [[Charles City (Virginia Company)|Charles City]], [[Elizabeth City (Virginia Company)|Elizabeth City]], Henrico City, and [[James City (Virginia Company)|James City]]. The latter included the seat of government for the colony at [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]]. Each of the four cities extended across the [[James River (Virginia)|James River]], the main conduit of transportation of the era.\n\nIn 1634, under Royal authority, a portion became Henrico Shire, later [[Henrico County, Virginia]].<ref name= Hening1809/> The [[county seat]] was designated near [[John Rolfe]] and [[Pocahontas]]' former home [[Varina Farms]] and remained there until 1752, when a new courthouse was built in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]].\n\nHenrico's first major settlement was in 1611 at the fortified town of [[Henricus]] on what is now known as [[Farrar's Island]],<ref name=Surface1907/> near the location of the [[Dutch Gap Canal]] today.  , Sir [[Thomas Dale]]'s , was abandoned during the [[Indian Massacre of 1622]], as were the [[Falling Creek Ironworks]]. However, the offshoot town of Henrico, as differentiated from the adjacent, defunct fort, would survive until 1786, its courthouse having been burned by [[Benedict Arnold]] in 1781, during the 1776 revolution. Both locations were recently rediscovered and are now located in [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield County]], which was formed from parts of Henrico before the [[American Revolutionary War]].\n\n\n\n\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name= Hening1809>{{cite book|chapter=Acts made at the Grand Assembly Holden at James {{not a typo|Citty}}, The 21st Aug, 1633|title= The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia, from the First Session of the Legislature, in the year 1619. Published Pursuant to an Act of the General Assembly of Virginia|editor= Hening, William Waller|date=1809|publisher= Richmond, VA: Samuel Pleasants, Jr., printer to the common wealth.|page=[https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/168 168]|url=https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/224/mode|editor-link=William Waller Hening|page=224}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/98|chapter=Virginia Company. Instructions to George Yeardley, November 18,1618|title=Records of the Virginia Company of London|volume=3|editor=Kingsbury, Susan Myra|editor-link=Susan Myra Kingsbury|publisher=Washington DC: Government Printing Office|date=1933|pages=98-109}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Surface1907>{{cite article|author=Surface, G. T.|title=Geographic Influence on the Economic History of Virginia|journal=Bulletin of the American geographical Society|vol=39|issue=7|date=1907|page=402|JSTOR=198932}}</ref>\n\n\n\n}}\n{{details|Henrico County, Virginia}}\n\n\n{{coord|37|22|54|N|77|20|09|W|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henrico City (Virginia Company)}}\n[[Category:Populated places in colonial Virginia]]\n[[Category:Henrico County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1619]]\n[[Category:1619 establishments in Virginia]]\n\n\n{{HenricoCountyVA-geo-stub}}\n{{US-hist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:1634 Virginia Counties- Henrico Focus.jpg||thumb|upright=2.0|The eight shires of Virginia created in 1634 with Henrico in purple]]\n{{see also|Henricus}}\n\n{{Unreferenced|date=January 2008}}\n'''Henrico City''' (or '''Henrico Cittie''' as it was then called) was one of four incorporations established in the [[Virginia Colony]] in 1619 North America by the proprietor, the [[Virginia Company]] in it instructions to Governor Yeardley in 1618. <ref name=Kingsbury1933v3/>. These instructions incorporated most of the plantations and developments of Virginia into four boroughs or cities. These cities were [[Charles City (Virginia Company)|Charles City]], [[Elizabeth City (Virginia Company)|Elizabeth City]], Henrico City, and [[James City (Virginia Company)|James City]]. The latter included the seat of government for the colony at [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]]. Each of the four cities extended across the [[James River (Virginia)|James River]], the main conduit of transportation of the era.\n\nIn 1634, under Royal authority, a portion became Henrico Shire, later [[Henrico County, Virginia]].<ref name= Hening1809/> The [[county seat]] was designated near [[John Rolfe]] and [[Pocahontas]]' former home [[Varina Farms]] and remained there until 1752, when a new courthouse was built in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]].\n\nHenrico's first major settlement was in 1611 at the fortified town of [[Henricus]] on what is now known as [[Farrar's Island]],<ref name=Surface1907/> near the location of the [[Dutch Gap Canal]] today.  , Sir [[Thomas Dale]]'s , was abandoned during the [[Indian Massacre of 1622]], as were the [[Falling Creek Ironworks]]. However, the offshoot town of Henrico, as differentiated from the adjacent, defunct fort, would survive until 1786, its courthouse having been burned by [[Benedict Arnold]] in 1781, during the 1776 revolution. Both locations were recently rediscovered and are now located in [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield County]], which was formed from parts of Henrico before the [[American Revolutionary War]].\n\n\n\n\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name= Hening1809>{{cite book|chapter=Acts made at the Grand Assembly Holden at James {{not a typo|Citty}}, The 21st Aug, 1633|title= The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia, from the First Session of the Legislature, in the year 1619. Published Pursuant to an Act of the General Assembly of Virginia|editor= Hening, William Waller|date=1809|publisher= Richmond, VA: Samuel Pleasants, Jr., printer to the common wealth.|page=[https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/168 168]|url=https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/224/mode|editor-link=William Waller Hening|page=224}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/98|chapter=Virginia Company. Instructions to George Yeardley, November 18,1618|title=Records of the Virginia Company of London|volume=3|editor=Kingsbury, Susan Myra|editor-link=Susan Myra Kingsbury|publisher=Washington DC: Government Printing Office|date=1933|pages=98-109}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Surface1907>{{cite article|author=Surface, G. T.|title=Geographic Influence on the Economic History of Virginia|Journal=Bulletin of the American geographical Society|vol=39|issue=7|date=1907|page=402|JSTOR=198932}}</ref>\n\n\n\n}}\n{{details|Henrico County, Virginia}}\n\n\n{{coord|37|22|54|N|77|20|09|W|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henrico City (Virginia Company)}}\n[[Category:Populated places in colonial Virginia]]\n[[Category:Henrico County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1619]]\n[[Category:1619 establishments in Virginia]]\n\n\n{{HenricoCountyVA-geo-stub}}\n{{US-hist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wtfiv", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henrico_City_(Virginia_Company)"}
{"title_page": "Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = the museum \n| native_name         = Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas\n| native_name_lang    = es\n| logo                = \n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Museo_arte_Caracas.JPG\n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_size            = \n| map_caption         = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|10.49847|-66.89964|format=dms|type:landmark_region:VE|display=title}}\n| former_name         = \n| established         = {{Start date|1973|08|30|df=y}} \n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| location            = [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]\n| type                = Museum of modern art\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = 5000\n| visitors            = \n| founder             = [[Sof\u00eda \u00cdmber]]\n| executive_director  = \n| leader_type         = \n| leader              = \n| director            = \n| president           = \n| ceo                 = \n| chairperson         = \n| curator             = \n| architect           = \n| historian           = \n| owner               = \n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = \n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embedded            = \n}}\n{{short description|Art museum in Caracas, Venezuela}}\n{{unreferenced|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Expand Spanish|Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art''' ({{Lang-es|1=''Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas'' or ''MACC''|italic=unset}}) is a museum of modern art located in the [[Parque Central Complex]] in [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1985|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1350-0775|via=}}</ref>. It was founded on 30 August 1973<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sartle.com/place/museum-of-contemporary-art-of-caracas|title=Museum of Contemporary Art of Caracas|date=2015-06-23|website=Sartle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> by the journalist and art patron [[Sof\u00eda \u00cdmber]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1987|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1350-0775|via=}}</ref>, also its director from 1973 to her dismissal in the [[Chavismo|Chavist]] cultural revolution of 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.sygic.com/en/poi/museum-of-contemporary-art-poi:29225|title=Museum of Contemporary Art in Caracas, Venezuela|last=s.r.o|first=Tripomatic|website=travel.sygic.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. It opened in 1974 and was the first museum in Venezuela to offer a specialist art library, a formal children's and adults' learning area, a special education department for the blind and a multimedia arts centre.\n\nIts collection has 5,000 pieces, including works by [[Pablo Picasso]], [[Claude Monet]], [[Vasili Kandinski]], [[Fernand L\u00e9ger]], [[Piet Mondrian]], [[Andy Warhol]] and [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1985|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|language=en|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1468-0033}}</ref> Its director's dismissal, the 2002 theft of [[Henri Matisse]]'s ''Odalisque in Red Pantaloons'' and the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan Crisis]] have involved the museum in corruption and neglect as well as leading to criticisms of poor security, rapid changes of directors and the cancellations of catalogues and exhibitions. Entry is free for the permanent collections and temporary exhibitions.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas}}\n\n[[category:Modern art museums]]\n[[category:1973 establishments in Venezuela]]\n[[category:Art museums and galleries in Caracas]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1973]]\n\n\n{{Venezuela-museum-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = the museum \n| native_name         = Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas\n| native_name_lang    = es\n| logo                = \n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Museo_arte_Caracas.JPG\n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_size            = \n| map_caption         = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|10.49847|-66.89964|format=dms|type:landmark_region:VE|display=title}}\n| former_name         = \n| established         = {{Start date|1973|08|30|df=y}} \n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| location            = [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]\n| type                = Museum of modern art\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = 5000\n| visitors            = \n| founder             = [[Sof\u00eda \u00cdmber]]\n| executive_director  = \n| leader_type         = \n| leader              = \n| director            = \n| president           = \n| ceo                 = \n| chairperson         = \n| curator             = \n| architect           = \n| historian           = \n| owner               = \n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = \n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embedded            = \n}}\n{{short description|Art museum in Caracas, Venezuela}}\n{{unreferenced|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Expand Spanish|Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art''' ({{Lang-es|1=''Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas'' or ''MACC''|italic=unset}}) is a museum of modern art located in the [[Parque Central Complex]] in [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1985|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1350-0775|via=}}</ref>. It was founded on 30 August 1973<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sartle.com/place/museum-of-contemporary-art-of-caracas|title=Museum of Contemporary Art of Caracas|date=2015-06-23|website=Sartle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> by the journalist and art patron [[Sof\u00eda \u00cdmber]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1987|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1350-0775|via=}}</ref>, also its director from 1973 to her dismissal in the [[Chavismo|Chavist]] cultural revolution of 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.sygic.com/en/poi/museum-of-contemporary-art-poi:29225|title=Museum of Contemporary Art in Caracas, Venezuela|last=s.r.o|first=Tripomatic|website=travel.sygic.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. It opened in 1974 and was the first museum in Venezuela to offer a specialist art library, a formal children's and adults' learning area, a special education department for the blind and a multimedia arts centre.\n\nIts collection has 5,000 pieces, including works by [[Pablo Picasso]], [[Claude Monet]], [[Vasili Kandinski]], [[Fernand L\u00e9ger]], [[Piet Mondrian]], [[Andy Warhol]] and [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]]. Its director's dismissal, the 2002 theft of [[Henri Matisse]]'s ''Odalisque in Red Pantaloons'' and the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan Crisis]] have involved the museum in corruption and neglect as well as leading to criticisms of poor security, rapid changes of directors and the cancellations of catalogues and exhibitions. Entry is free for the permanent collections and temporary exhibitions.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas}}\n\n[[category:Modern art museums]]\n[[category:1973 establishments in Venezuela]]\n[[category:Art museums and galleries in Caracas]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1973]]\n\n\n{{Venezuela-museum-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pishi25", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caracas_Museum_of_Contemporary_Art"}
